Problem Definition¶

Background:
what exactly makes an airline the best airline in the world?This dataset contains an airline passenger satisfaction survey. What factors are highly correlated to a satisfied (or dissatisfied) passenger? To predict passenger satisfaction.

The problem questions:
a. How can airlines know which factors are most important for/the strongest contributors to customer satisfaction?
b. Which factors contributing to satisfaction correlate with one another?
c. Are a random set of customers more likely to be satisfied or neutral/dissatisfied with an airline experience?

Objective:
Clean, fit a model to predict, and visualize & interpret the passenger satisfaction data to find the relationships between category ratings and overall satisfaction of the passenger, as well as evaluate the results.

Dataset¶

Gender: Unveil the diversity of passengers with two distinct values, offering insights into the gender distribution and its potential influence on satisfaction.

Customer Type: Distinguish between regular customers and those with a different status. Understand how service preferences might vary between these customer types.

Age: Embark on a journey through age demographics with 75 unique values. Discover the range of ages among passengers, contributing to a nuanced understanding of their preferences. Generation feature was created from age range.

Type of Travel: Uncover the purpose behind each journeybusiness or leisure. The Type of Travel column reveals the diverse motivations that shape passenger experiences.

Class: Explore the array of travel classes with three unique values. Delve into the world of passenger preferences across different service levels.

Flight Distance: Navigate through 3821 unique values, representing a comprehensive range of distances traveled. Gain insights into satisfaction trends across varying journey lengths.

Service Ratings: Encounter multiple columns assessing different in-flight services, each offering six unique values. These ratings paint a detailed picture of passenger experiences, providing a holistic view of service quality.

Departure and Arrival Delays: Experience the ebb and flow of time with Departure Delay in Minutes' and 'Arrival Delay in Minutes. With a range of 464 to 472 unique values, understand the impact of delays on passenger satisfaction.

Satisfaction: Unveil the essence of the datasetthe Satisfaction column. With two unique values, this column serves as the bedrock for predictive modeling, unlocking the secrets behind passenger contentment or discontent.

Target Variable The primary target for analysis is the satisfaction column in the dataset.

def draw_categorical_plot(data, figsize=(8, 6), colors=None):
    
    if not isinstance(data, pd.Series):
        raise ValueError("Input data should be a categorical data.")
    
    # Count the occurrences of each category in the data
    counts = data.value_counts()
    
    # Create a figure and axes
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
    
    # If there are less than 6 unique observations, draw a pie chart
    if len(counts) <= 5:
        counts.plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%', colors=colors, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title("Pie Chart of " + data.name)
        ax.set_ylabel("")  # This is to remove the column name from the side of the pie chart
    else:
        # Otherwise, draw a bar chart
        sns.barplot(x=counts.index, y=counts.values, palette=colors, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title("Bar Chart of " + data.name)
        ax.set_ylabel("Count")
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()  # Display the plot

Departure and Arrival Time Convenience: The ratings are almost evenly distributed between 1 and 5. For instance, most people that rated the convience with 4 are also neutral or dissatisfied and the rest are close to 50-50.

Ease of Online Booking: First of all, the average rating seems to be neutral since most of the Passengers have rated between 2 and 4. It seems that passengers value the ease of online booking. Most passengers that have rated 1 through 3 have also been Neutral or Dissatisfied with the overall experience.Plus, most of the passengers that gave a 5 also have been satisfied with the experience which proves the point I am trying to make above.

Check-in Services: The good news is that only one passenger has rated with 0. The overall experience with check-in seems to be pleasant (most ratings are 3-5).Furthermore, the bad experiences with check-in, which equal to bad reviews as well, seem to have a big effect on the overall experiences of the passengers (Most are Neutral or Dissatisfied).

Online Boarding: In this rating we see a huge association between the satisfaction on Online Boarding and the overall experience of the passenger. In more detail, the people that gave a low rating on online boarding are also neutral or dissatisfied and those with a high rating are satisfied with the overall experience. Most passengers have rated between 3 and 5 which is a good sign but it seems like there is room for improvement, especially when it is a feature that passengers deem to be important.

Gate Location: The ratings on Gate Location are evenly spread out with most of them being positive. The Gate location doesn't have much gravity on the total satisfaction. The satisfaction is split almost 50-50 on every rating expect 3 but we can't make any assumptions from that because the rest of the ratings are almost evenly distributed, so it is probably a coincidence.

Onboard services: Most reviews are from 3 to 5, which is something positive. On the other hand, the passengers that had a bad experience with the on-board service are also neutral or dissatisfied overall. This makes us come to the conclusion that a passenger's experience is hugely affect by the on-board service, which is something logical.

Seat Comfort: Again, the majority of the reviews are positive (3 to 5). On the other hand, the people that were dissatisfied by the seat comfort seem to have a bad experience overall. Most of the 1-2 ratings are neutral or dissatisfied. This shows us, that the airline should have seat comfort as a priority in order to offer the passenger a pleasant experience overall.

Leg Room Service: The leg room ratings are similar to the seat comfort ratings which is something logical. Most reviews are positive and it has a big impact on the overall experience of the passenger. At this point it is important to note that both leg room service and seat comfort are also very dependant on the class the passenger is flying on. For example, many airlines charge extra for more leg room.

Cleanliness: Most of the ratings in this category are between 3-5 which is positive. The only correlation between the overall experience and cleanliness is at the lower ratings 1-2, where passengers are mostly neutral or dissatisfied.

Food and Drink: This category is also very dependant on the class the passenger is flying on. With that in mind, the ratings are very evenly splitted between 2-5. Again, in the negative ratings (1-2) the majority of people and neutral or dissatisfied. Inflight Service: The majority of the reviews are between 3-5, which is very positive. There are very few low ratings so there is not much to analyze there. The overall satisfaction is mostly neutral or dissatisfied at the low ratings but it gets better on ratings 4 and 5.

Inflight Wi-fi Service: Most of the ratings are between 2-4 so the overall ratings is average. Looking at the data (todays society) passengers with bad wifi experience (1-3) are mostly neutral or dissatisfied, which is something that makes sense since in today's age wifi is a very important tool in our daily lives. In another note, it is important to remember that airlines charge extra for a better wifi experience and the wifi speed is also dependant on the class the passenger is flying.

Inflight Etertainment: The majority of the reviews are positive and most of them are between 4-5.From the plot above, we realise that In-flight entertainment has a big impact on the overall satisfaction of the passenger. In more detail, we can clearly see that people with negative or neutral experience (0-3) are mostly neutral or dissatisfied, whereas people with a positive experience are mostly overall satisfied.

Bagage Handling: Another important feature is baggage handling. The majority of the reviews are positive and neutral (3-5). Noteable observations:¶

  1. The ratings of ease of online booking and inflight wifi service are two of the most strongly correlated variables with one another, with an r value of 0.72.

  2. Cleanliness ratings have a relatively strong positive correlation with food and drink, seat comfort, and inflight entertainment ratings.

  3. Out of all of the individual factors, online boarding ratings have the strongest positive relationship to satisfaction. However, it is still not necessarily a strong correlation as the r value is only 0.5.

  4. Baggage handling and inflight service have a relatively strong positive correlation (r=0.63).

  5. Gate location has the weakest relationship to satisfaction (r=0.00068)

  6. We can see that there is a match between arrival delay and departure delay which is expected.

  7. Passenger satisfaction is dependent on all of the features of the dataset (Online Boarding, Seat Comfort etc.) almost equally.

Overall, there are not many categories that seem to have a significantly strong relationship relative to others with another category, as well as with total satisfaction. It may be beneficial to group some of the specific categories together into slightly broader categories and compute their relationship to satisfaction in a different manner, as factors put together may have a larger impact on satisfaction.

DATA PRE-PROCESSING¶

In order to streamline the analysis, I decided to create broader categories out of the ones that currently exist in the dataset:
1. Time and Location: 'Departure and arrival time convenient," "Gate location"
2. Inflight Entertainment: 'Inflight wifi service,' 'inflight entertainment'
3. Online services: 'Ease of Online booking', 'Online boarding'
4. Food and drink
5. Comfort: 'Leg room service', 'seat comfort'
6. Cleanliness
7. Service: 'Boarding service', 'Baggage handling', 'Checkin service', 'Inflight service'

These new categories will help make analysis simpler, under the assumption that subcategories in each broader categories are related to one another in terms of their performance. For example, good leg room is expected to relate to good seat comfort, and ease of online booking would also relate to ease of online check-in.

Methodology for combining colunms: The average rating within each of these categories will be calculated for each customer, and then each category will be compared with another in order to see which one has the greatest effect on overall satisfaction and average rating.

Dataset Splitting:
For model development, the dataset was split into training (60%), testing (20%), and validation (20%) sets.

Label Encoder:
Label Encoding is a technique that is used to convert categorical columns into numerical ones so that they can be fitted by machine learning models which only take numerical data. It is an important pre-processing step in a machine-learning project.

Standardization:
A standard scaler was applied to standardize the data, bringing features to a common scale. This preprocessing step is essential for optimizing machine learning algorithms and ensuring fair contributions from each feature in subsequent analyses.

In [22]:
df = pd.read_csv("airline_passenger_satisfaction.csv")

#Adding columns for the average ratings of each of the new categories
df['Time and Location']=(df['Departure and Arrival Time Convenience'] + df['Gate Location'])/2
df['Inflight Entertainment']= (df['In-flight Wifi Service'] + df['In-flight Entertainment'])/2
df['Online Services'] = (df['Ease of Online Booking'] + df['Online Boarding'])/2
df['Comfort'] = (df['Leg Room Service'] + df['Seat Comfort'])/2
df['Service']=(df['On-board Service'] + df['Check-in Service']+df['Baggage Handling']+df['In-flight Service'])/4

# Fill null values as 0
df.fillna(0,inplace=True)

MODEL BUILDING USING SUPERVISED LEARNING ALGORITHMS¶

Packages used¶

sklearn: Scikit-learn (Sklearn) is the most useful and robust library for machine learning in Python. It provides a selection of efficient tools for machine learning and statistical modeling including classification, regression, clustering and dimensionality reduction via a consistence interface in Python. This library, which is largely written in Python, is built upon NumPy, SciPy and Matplotlib.

Supervised Learning Algorithms¶

Definition: Supervised learning is an approach to creating artificial intelligence ( AI) where a computer algorithm is trained on input data that has been labeled for a particular output.

Logistics Regression

  1. Logistic regression is a supervised machine learning algorithm mainly used for binary classification where we use a logistic function, also known as a sigmoid function that takes input as independent variables and produces a probability value between 0 and 1.
  2. Utilizing BayesianCV
  3. Best Parameters: C: 0.0306, Fit Intercept: True, Penalty: L1, Solver: Liblinear

Decision Tree Classifier

  1. A decision tree is one of the most powerful tools of supervised learning algorithms used for both classification and regression tasks. It builds a flowchart-like tree structure where each internal node denotes a test on an attribute, each branch represents an outcome of the test, and each leaf node (terminal node) holds a class label.
  2. Utilizing BayesianCV
  3. Best Hyperparameters: Criterion: Entropy, Max Depth: 15, Min Samples Leaf: 1, Min Samples Split: 10

Random Forest Classifier

  1. Random forest is a supervised machine learning algorithm that uses a number of decision trees to perform classification or regression tasks. It creates a set of decision trees from randomly selected subsets of the training set and takes the average of their predictions. Random forest reduces the overfitting of the dataset and improves the accuracy of the results
In [29]:
# LOGISTIC REGRESSION
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
lr = LogisticRegression(C=0.030571559019667797, fit_intercept=True, penalty='l1', solver='liblinear')
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_lr = lr.predict(X_test)

# DECISION TREE CLASSIFIER
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', max_depth=15, min_samples_leaf=1, min_samples_split=10)
dt.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_dt = dt.predict(X_test)

# RANDOM FOREST CLASSIFIER
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
rf = RandomForestClassifier()
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_rf = rf.predict(X_test)

Model evaluation¶

Model evaluation encompasses key metrics on both the test and validation sets:

  1. Confusion matrix
  2. Accuracy score - Accuracy score is a measure of how well a model can correctly classify or predict data.
  3. Precision score - The precision is the ratio tp / (tp + fp) where tp is the number of true positives and fp the number of false positives.
  4. Recall score - The recall is the ratio of True Positive and the sum of True Positive and False Negative.
  5. F1 score - F1 score gives the combined result of Precision and Recall. It is a Harmonic Mean of Precision and Recall.

Validation Set: The same metrics were applied, ensuring consistency and reliability across different datasets.

Precision-Recall Curve: Plots for each model on the validation set provide insights into precision-recall trade-offs, especially in imbalanced scenarios.

K-Fold Cross Validation: Employed to enhance reliability by training and testing the model on different folds, minimizing the impact of dataset variability on assessments.

In [30]:

Precision Recall curve¶

A precision-recall curve is a plot that shows the trade-off between the precision and the recall of a classifier at different thresholds.

In [35]:
# Create a dictionary to store the predictions for each model
y_pred_val_dict = {
    'Logistic Regression': y_pred_val_lr,
    'Decision Tree': y_pred_val_dt,
    'Random Forest': y_pred_val_rf
}

# Plot Precision-Recall curves for each model
for index, row in validation_results_df.iterrows():
    model_name = row['Model']
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_val, y_pred_val_dict[model_name])

    # Plot Precision-Recall curve
    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=model_name)

# Customize the plot
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve - Validation Set')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

The precision-recall curve shows the tradeoff between precision and recall for different threshold. A high area under the curve represents both high recall and high precision, where high precision relates to a low false positive rate, and high recall relates to a low false negative rate. Above graph has both high recall and high precision.

K-FOLD Crossvalidation on Random forest algorithm¶

Cross-validation is a statistical method used to estimate the skill of machine learning models.

It is commonly used in applied machine learning to compare and select a model for a given predictive modeling problem because it is easy to understand, easy to implement, and results in skill estimates that generally have a lower bias than other methods.

K-fold is a type of crossvalidation technique

K-fold
The procedure has a single parameter called k that refers to the number of groups that a given data sample is to be split into. As such, the procedure is often called k-fold cross-validation. When a specific value for k is chosen, it may be used in place of k in the reference to the model, such as k=10 becoming 10-fold cross-validation.

In [36]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, KFold

num_folds = 5
kf = KFold(n_splits=num_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Perform cross-validation
cv_scores_lr = cross_val_score(lr, X_train, y_train, cv=kf, scoring='accuracy')
cv_scores_dt = cross_val_score(dt, X_train, y_train, cv=kf, scoring='accuracy')
cv_scores_rf = cross_val_score(rf, X_train, y_train, cv=kf, scoring='accuracy')

# Print the cross-validation scores
print("LOGISTIC REGRESSION")
print("K-Fold Cross-validation scores:", cv_scores_lr)
print("Mean accuracy:", np.mean(cv_scores_lr))
print("="*33)

print("DECISION TREE CLASSIFIER")
print("K-Fold Cross-validation scores:", cv_scores_dt)
print("Mean accuracy:", np.mean(cv_scores_dt))
print("="*33)

print("RANDOM FOREST CLASSIFIER")
print("K-Fold Cross-validation scores:", cv_scores_rf)
print("Mean accuracy:", np.mean(cv_scores_rf))
